hitectural space: how it could be navigated, inhabited, and designed to reflect the modern way of life while also offering respite from it.The New Space traces the theoretical conversation about space carried out in the writings and built works of Loos, Frank, and Strnad over four decades. The three ultimately explored what Le Corbusier would later-independently-term the architectural promenade. Lavishly illustrated with new photography and architectural plans, this important book enhances our understanding of the development of modernism and of architectural theory and practice.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 0aArchitectszAustriazViennaxHistory. 0aArchitecturezAustriazViennaxHistory. 0aArchitecture, DomesticzAustriazViennaxHistoryy20th century. 0aModern movement (Architecture)zAustriazVienna. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2017z978311063898140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300223927423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300223927.jpg  a978-3-11-063898-1  YUP eBook Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles